commit.message:
Add sticky window/client support (#1542)

This PR implements sticky windows/clients as discussed in #976.

Anything I use this feature for works without issues, but I'll test a few days/weeks for bugs.

Clients always stay on the monitor they are on. This is how bspwm handles sticky windows too. When tags are swapped between two monitors, the sticky windows are swapped too, so that they stay on the correct monitor. Sticky windows stay focused when switching tags, but do not gain focus if they were previously not foucsed. Rule support is added too and works.

commit.message:
Re-enable using double hyphens before rule options (#1524)

Previously, double hyphens were stripped in the tokenizeArg function which is only called after checking if the argument is "prepend", "once", "printlabel", "not", "!", or "fixedwidth". This failed to match on "--once", "--prepend", etc..., so the argument is eventually passed to tokenizeArg. But tokenizeArg expects all of its arguments to contain a = or ~ (everything else was supposed to be handled already). This resulted in an error.

Now, the stripping of hyphens is done at the beginning of rule parsing, and after manually moving the loop pointer for "not" and "!".

This closes #1487

commit.message:
Make geometry based panel detection an attribute (#1521)

If a panel does not define _NET_WM_STRUT, we formerly just used it's window size for determining the reserved space at the screen edge. This caused issues such as #1475. By making it a setting, only those users who really need it can activate it.

While at it, I've fixed a bug in `Signal::connect()` arising from a wrong use of `std::bind()`.

This closes #1475 and #1175.

commit.message:
Css: Only load font when needed (#1517)

Introduce a new default value for fonts 'initial'. The value resolves to
an arbitrary font in the rare occassion that it is actually used for
rendering text. By this, we fix the following:

  1. the empty string "" should not be a valid font description.
  2. shared pointers of FontData objects (for "") should not be copied
     all over the place when BoxStyles are inherited.

commit.message:
tests: Improve stdout/stderr synchronization (#1511)

Before, running an ordinary hlwm.call() in a wait_stdout_match() context
consumed the token we were waiting for, making to context fail.

The present change fixes this by improves read_and_echo_output() to
support scanning for multiple tokens at the same time. This makes the
wait_stdout_match() contexts much easier to use.

CSS-inspired theme engine for client decorations (#1457)

We apply the CSS engine to the theming of clients. So instead of the
explicit client decoration drawing, we have a generic CSS-based widget
render and the existing theme attributes generate a stylesheet.
There is no documentation yet, but two example themes.


This closes #1433.

commit.message: www: Add 0.9.5 tarball
Release 0.9.5

Introduce %{ } format for sprintf (#1481)

In foreach loops and other meta commands, one often needs to first
compose an attribute path and then look up its value. The present change
simplifies this to one step:

    sprintf S '%{%c.count}' tags echo S

will print the value of `tags.count`. With this new format, `%s` is
equivalent to `%{%c}`.

commit.message:
IPC Server: fix type of command status (#1502)

The Xlib function XChangeProperty() requires the data array to be
an array of 'long'. This causes wrong behaviour if long is larger than
int and if byte order is big-endian.

I could reproduce the issue #1414 on the ppc64 system gcc203 of the
gcc compile farm. Unfortunately, I don't see how I can verify the now
fixed issue in a test case.

There is another issue in the status property: the atom should have type
XA_CARDINAL instead of XA_ATOM. Changing this would require the
corresponding change in herbstclient. Strictly speaking, this would be
an incompatible change in the IPC protocol.

This fixes #1414.

commit.message:
tests: Work around endianess in image data (#1501)

The raw data of an image obtained from a screenshot depends on the
endianess. I couldn't make colormap.query_colors() work for depth 32 or
24, which would be the clean solution. Instead, we still parse the
binary image data manually and depend on the endianess of the system. In
principle, this could still be different from the image's endianess in
distributed X11 setups, but this should not happen when running the test
suite.

I could reproduce the issue #1486 on the ppc64 system gcc203 of the
gcc compile farm.

This fixes #1486.
